04656nam a22005295i 9780231555432DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315554327 a10.7312/schl204222doi  a(DE-B1597)670313  a(OCoLC)1378065985  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHV551.2b.S384 2023 7aSOC0400002bisacsh04a363.34/8223/eng/202305011 aSchlegelmilch, Jeff, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCatastrophic Incentives :bWhy Our Approaches to Disasters Keep Falling Short /cJeff Schlegelmilch, Ellen Carlin. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAcronyms and Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tPart I: A Recent History of Disasters: Events, Trends and Organizational Responses -- t1. The Birth of the Modern Era of U.S. Disaster Management and Its Global Implications (2001) -- t2. A Pandemic Warning, Earthquakes, Tsunamis, Hurricane Katrina, and a Bird Flu (2002–2007) -- t3. An Influenza Pandemic, Earthquake in Haiti, Fukushima Disaster, and Superstorm Sandy (2008– 2012) -- t4. Ebola, Hurricanes, Wildfires, and a Pandemic for the Ages (2013– 2021) -- tPart II. How Organizations Respond to Disasters and Why They Behave That Way -- t5. Disaster Politics -- t6. Disaster Markets and the Private Sector -- t7. Disaster Nonprofits -- t8. Disaster Academics -- tPart III: In Search of Disaster Resilience -- t9. Humans Are Bad at Risk, and Even Worse with Uncertainty -- t10. Reimagining the Model -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSocieties are vulnerable to any number of potential disasters: earthquakes, hurricanes, infectious diseases, terrorist attacks, and many others. Even though the dangers are often clear, there is a persistent pattern of inadequate preparation and a failure to learn from experience. Before disasters, institutions pay insufficient attention to risk; in the aftermath, even when the lack of preparation led to a flawed response, the focus shifts to patching holes instead of addressing the underlying problems.Examining twenty years of disasters from 9/11 to COVID-19, Jeff Schlegelmilch and Ellen Carlin show how flawed incentive structures make the world more vulnerable when catastrophe strikes. They explore how governments, the private sector, nonprofits, and academia behave before, during, and after crises, arguing that standard operational and business models have produced dysfunction. Catastrophic Incentives reveals troubling patterns about what does and does not matter to the institutions that are responsible for dealing with disasters. The short-termism of electoral politics and corporate decision making, the funding structure of nonprofits, and the institutional dynamics shaping academic research have all contributed to a failure to build resilience.Offering a comprehensive and incisive look at disaster governance, Catastrophic Incentives provides timely recommendations for reimagining systems and institutions so that they are better equipped to manage twenty-first-century threats.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDisaster reliefxPolitical aspects. 0aEmergency managementxPolitical aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Disasters & Disaster Relief.2bisacsh1 aCarlin, Ellen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074967040uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/schl2042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231555432423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/97